Regulators of G protein signaling proteins (RGSs) can be coordinated by both platelet agonists (eg, thrombin) or platelet inhibitors (eg, prostacyclin) to dampen persistent platelet activation that does not then become physiologically inappropriate. Conversely, binding of thrombin, ADP, and thromboxane A2 to G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) leads to platelet activation.
